You can add your voice to the tens of thousands of comments posted daily on Express.co.uk and have your say on the big issues facing the country today. The Department for Work & Pensions is poised to push up the State Pension age, with the limit rising from 66 to 70. State Pension ages will climb to 66 to 67 from 2026 to 2028 before rising to 68 between 2037 and 2039, ditching the previous 2044 to 2046 plans. And experts say it won't stop there, climbing to 70 in just a few more years. Officials say the decision will ease the burden on the Treasury but Daily Express personal finance editor Harvey Jones accused the DWP of being "hellbent on making us work until we drop." Expert calls to reduce the age as life expectancy falls have gathered momentum over the last year, with data showing a decline for those retiring by 66. Pressure is mounting on Rishi Sunak to intervene as the changes will mean people retiring around the state pension age live two years less than previous generations, so should the Chancellor ensure the retirement age reflects this? HAVE YOUR SAY RIGHT NOW - JOIN THE EXPRESS READER DEBATE IN OUR COMMENTS SECTION.